The Gauss-Kuzmin-Wirsing Operator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The map that that acts as the shift operator for continued fractions is
 
\begin_inset Formula \[
h(x)=\frac{1}{x}-\left\lfloor \frac{1}{x}\right\rfloor \]

\end_inset

That is, if one writes out the continued-fraction expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
x=\frac{1}{a_{1}+\frac{1}{a_{2}+\frac{1}{a_{3}+\cdots}}}\equiv\left[a_{1},a_{2},a_{3},\cdots\right]\label{eq:continued-frac}\end{equation}

\end_inset

then one has that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
h(x)=\left[a_{2},a_{3},\cdots\right]\]

\end_inset

whence the name 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shift operator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 This map is often called the Gauss Map.
 Note that shift operators, as linear operators, are studied as a subtopic
 of Banach theory, and often appear in applied mathematics texts devoted
 to the engineering topics of control theory, stability theory and filter
 design
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Part2004"

\end_inset

.
 However, in these texts, shift operators are typically applied to sequences
 of functions defined on Hardy spaces.
 It appears that the shift as applied to continued fractions is very nearly
 unstudied -- and no wonder -- it appears nearly intractable when approached
 with standard analytic tools.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Ruelle-Frobenius-Perron or transfer operator associated with the Gauss
 map is known as the Gauss-Kuzmin-Wirsing (GKW)
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kuzmin1928,Wirsing1974"

\end_inset

 operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}$
\end_inset

.
 It is the pushback of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, and as such, is a linear map between spaces of functions on the unit interval
 (topological vector spaces)
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vep-mink2008"

\end_inset

.
 That is, given the vector space of functions from the closed unit interval
 to the real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{F}=\left\{ f\,|\, f:\left[0,1\right]\to\mathbb{R}\right\} \]

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}$
\end_inset

 is a linear operator mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 .
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, it is represented by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}f\right](x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{(n+x)^{2}}f\left(\frac{1}{n+x}\right)\label{eq:sum-form}\end{equation}

\end_inset

This operator is bounded; its largest eigenvalue is 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The GKW operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}$
\end_inset

 is a special case of what is sometimes called the Ruelle-Mayer operator
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Flajolet1997"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[G_{s}f\right](z)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{(n+z)^{s}}f\left(\frac{1}{n+z}\right)\]

\end_inset

for general complex 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 This operator, with a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $s=4$
\end_inset

, occurs in the study of the Gaussian reduction algorithm applied to modular
 lattices
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Flajolet1997"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Niether the GKW nor the Mayer-Ruelle operators have been 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

solved
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, in the sense that there is no known closed-form analytic solution expressing
 its all of its eigenfunctions and eigenvectors.
 The GKW operator has one classically known eigenvector, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=1/(1+x)$
\end_inset

, which corresponds to the unit eigenvalue; this solution was given by Gauss.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Kuzmin considers iterating this operator, and shows that given any continuous,
 differentiable function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 with bounded derivative on the unit interval, that the iterate converges
 uniformly to 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=C/(1+x)$
\end_inset

.
 That is, by defining 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{k+1}(x)=\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}g_{k}\right](x)\]

\end_inset

 as the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th iterate of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{k}(x)\to C/(1+x)$
\end_inset

 uniformly, for all bounded, differentiable 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, as a corollary, this eigenvector is unique
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "section 15"
key "Khin35"

\end_inset

.
 An alternative way of understanding this result is via the Frobenius-Perron
 theorem, which asserts that the eigenfunction associated with the maximal
 eigenvalue is unique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The operator is not normal (
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}\mathcal{L}_{h}^{T}$
\end_inset

 is not equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}^{T}\mathcal{L}_{h}$
\end_inset

); this is typically the case for transfer operators.
 Thus, the left and right eigenvectors are distinct, although they share
 common eigenvalues.
 To use proper matrix algebra language, these should be called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

singular values
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, although we will persist in calling them eigenvalues below; and likewise
 diagonalization should properly be called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

singular value decomposition
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and the left and right eigenvectors are properly called the left and right
 singular vectors.
 Alternately, if one considers the operator as acting on a Banach space,
 then right singular vectors form a basis for for the Banach space, and
 the left vectors are the dual.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the domain of the Mayer-Ruelle operator is restricted to certain Banach
 spaces, then the operator is a nuclear operator -- that is, it has a discrete
 spectrum, and its eigenvectors form a basis for Banach space.
 By considering the operator restricted to a Hardy space, Daud√© 
\emph on
etal
\emph default
 show that the spectrum is real when 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is real
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Flajolet1997"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first eigenvalue below 1.0 is approximately 0.3036, and is known as the
 GKW constant 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Briggs2003,Flajolet1995,Flajolet1997"

\end_inset

[xxx need Babenko ref for original discussion].
 As is typically the case for transfer operators, when the right eigenvectors
 are smooth functions, then the left eigenvectors are linear combinations
 of derivatives of Dirac delta functions, located at 0 and 1.
 All of this is explored in greater detail, in the rest of this paper.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Aside from the analytic solutions, there is also large class of fractal,
 discontinuous-everywhere functions associated with eigenvalue 1.
 The prototypical such solution is the derivative of the Minkowski Question
 Mark function 
\begin_inset Formula $?(x)$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}?^{\prime}\right](x)=?^{\prime}(x)\]

\end_inset

A proper construction for the everywhere-discontinuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $?^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, and the derivation of the above identity, is given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vep-mink2008"

\end_inset

, together with a construction of a class of other similar solutions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Relation to the Riemann Zeta Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Gauss map is connected to the Riemann zeta function by a Mellin Transform:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\zeta(s)=\frac{1}{s-1}-s\int_{0}^{1}h(x)\, x^{s-1}dx\]

\end_inset

The Riemann zeta can be written under a change of variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y=h\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\zeta(s)=\frac{s}{s-1}-s\int_{0}^{1}dx\; x\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}x^{s-1}\right]\label{eq:zeta-gkw}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and thus it seems possible that a better understanding of GKW may shed light
 on the Riemann Hypothesis and/or the Berry conjecture[xxx need ref].
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Curiously, the above equation can be understood to be a kind of linear equation
 specifying the Riemann zeta, because the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}$
\end_inset

 is a constant, independent of the integration variable, and can be pulled
 out of the integral.
 For a suitable basis, the integral can become easy to evaluate, leaving
 a linear equation, albeit depending on a paramter 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 in a non-linear way.
 Sketching this out breifly, suppose one has a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ e_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 for the unit interval, so that one can write 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=\sum_{n}f_{n}e_{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In this basis, the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}$
\end_inset

 will have matrix elements 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{jk}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}f\right]\left(x\right)=\sum_{jk}L_{jk}f_{k}e_{j}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Supposing now that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is just 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{s-1}$
\end_inset

, and that the order of summation and integration can be exchanged, this
 leaves only the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int xe_{j}\left(x\right)dx$
\end_inset

 to evalute, which can then be replaced in the sum: 
\begin_inset Formula $\int dx\; x\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}x^{s-1}\right]=\sum_{jk}L_{jk}f_{k}\int xe_{j}\left(x\right)dx$
\end_inset

.
 This last is then a linear equation, althought the 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{k}$
\end_inset

 depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 in a non-linear way.
 The collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ f_{k}\right\} $
\end_inset

 can be thought of as a vector in an infinite-dimensional space; this vector
 depends on a single parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 As the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is varied, there are special values of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 where its product times the linear operator is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\left(s-1\right)$
\end_inset

: these special values of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 are nothing but the zeroes of the Riemann zeta.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Polynomial-Representation"

\end_inset

 provides explicit expressions for the matrix elements 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{jk}$
\end_inset

 for the polynomial basis 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{n}\left(x\right)=x^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, the integral becomes trivial to evaluate, and one discovers
 a series expansion for the Riemann zeta in terms of the falling factorial
 (equivalently, binomial coefficients).
 This series has many interesting properties, and is explored in greater
 detail in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vep-zeta2004,Fla06"

\end_inset

.
 The series generalizes; it can be used to formulate a class of criteria
 on various number-theortic series (such as those constructed from the Mobius
 function, or the totient function of the Liouville series) that are equivalent
 to the Riemann Hypothesis.
 This class of RH-equivalent hypothesis were already noted by B√°ez-Duarte
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ba03,Baez2005"

\end_inset

, Maslanka
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Maslanka2006"

\end_inset

, and Flajolet and Vall√©e
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Flajolet2000"

\end_inset

, and are explored in detail in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vep-norlund-2006"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Far more promising, however, are basis functions derived from or structured
 on the Cantor set.
 These are explored below, and in other related papers [xxx need ref].
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Lack of simple solutions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Aside from the classical solution, 
\begin_inset Formula $1/(1+x)$
\end_inset

, there do not seem to be any 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

easy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 polynomial series solutions to the operator, where a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

solution
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 would be a closed-form specification of the eigenvectors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The author performed a combinatorial search of simple combinations and summation
s of rational functions and various classical functions, such as the exponential
, the gamma, the digamma, the dilogarithm, Bessel functions and the exponential
 integral.
 No eigenvectors were found in this way, although, of course, various close
 approximations can be so obtained.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The naivest approaches to solving the GKW operator, which is suggested by
 the eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:sum-form"

\end_inset

, is blocked by the next two theorems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
There is no (non-trivial) polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\tau)$
\end_inset

 such that the equation 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f\left(\frac{1}{\tau+n}\right)=\lambda_{n}\left(\tau+n\right)^{2}f\left(\tau\right)\]

\end_inset

 holds for all integer values of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and arbitrary values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Assume that there does exist such a solution.
 Then it could be written as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f\left(\tau\right)=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}a_{k}\tau^{k}\]

\end_inset

for some unknown values of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

 (which are independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

).
 Inserting this into the hypothetical form leads to the equation 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\lambda_{n}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\tau^{k}\left[a_{k-2}+2na_{k-1}+n^{2}a_{k}\right] & =\\
\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\tau^{k}\frac{\left(-1\right)^{k}}{n^{k}}\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}a_{j}{j+k-1 \choose j-1}\frac{1}{n^{j}}\end{align*}

\end_inset

Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=1$
\end_inset

 in the above allows it to be re-written as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lambda_{n}\left(n-1\right)^{2}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\left(-1\right)^{k}a_{k}=a_{0}+\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}n^{-k}\sum_{j=0}^{k}{k \choose j}\, a_{j+1}\]

\end_inset

Since the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

 are independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 by assumption, one must then have 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}=0$
\end_inset

, and for each term in the series on the right hand side, one must have,
 individually, that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
0=\sum_{j=0}^{k}{k \choose j}\, a_{j+1}\]

\end_inset

or 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the theorem is proved.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Were it not for this theorem, a solution would have been provided by looking
 for quasi-modular-form-like functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Another naive avenue is also blocked: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
There is only one series solution to 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f\left(\frac{1}{\tau+n}\right)=\frac{\left(\tau+n\right)\left(\tau+1\right)}{\left(\tau+n+1\right)}\lambda f\left(\tau\right)\]

\end_inset

and it is 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\tau\right)=a_{0}/\left(1+\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 for any constant 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
As in the previous proof, assume a series solution.
 Substituting this into the above, and performing a straightforward but
 tedious expansion in powers of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and then comparing terms, reveals that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}=\left(-1\right)^{k}a_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the above had allowed solutions for something other than 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

, then one would have also had that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}f=\lambda f$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Assorted Algebraic Identities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section lists an assortment of random algebraic results, none particularly
 deep; some are vaguely suggestive of deeper relations.
 These are listed here mostly for the sake of completeness.
 These are the sorts of identities one obtains by means of knuckle-headed
 persistence in the hope that that maybe one little algebraic twist will
 yield a closed-form solution.
 These were obtained by the author long before he knew that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}$
\end_inset

 had a name or had been previously studied by others.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, notice that adjacent terms in the series can be made to cancel by
 shifting the series by one:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}f\right](x)-\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}f\right](x+1)=\frac{1}{(1+x)^{2}}f\left(\frac{1}{1+x}\right)\]

\end_inset

which holds for any function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x).$
\end_inset

 Thus, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x)$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}\rho=\lambda\rho$
\end_inset

, then it would also solve 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{1}{(1+x)^{2}}\rho\left(\frac{1}{1+x}\right)=\lambda\left(\rho(x)-\rho(x+1)\right)\]

\end_inset

This can be solved easily to get the zeroth eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\rho_{0}(x)=\frac{1}{\ln2}\;\frac{1}{1+x}\]

\end_inset

which satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathcal{L}_{h}\rho_{0}](x)=\rho_{0}(x)$
\end_inset

 and the normalization is given by requiring 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{0}^{1}\rho_{0}(x)\, dx=1\]

\end_inset

There is a reflection identity: 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=1-(1+x)^{-2}$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}f=1-f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a hint of a relationship between period-doubling and the GKW in
 the identity 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{1}{1+x}=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\,\frac{1}{2^{n}}\left[\frac{2}{x+n}-\frac{1}{x+n+1}\right]\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Acting on the monomial, one gets 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}x^{k}\right](x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\,\frac{1}{(n+x)^{k+2}}=\frac{(-)^{k+2}}{(k+1)!}\psi^{(k+1)}(1+x)\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi^{(k)}(x)$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th derivative of the Gamma function.
 The true difficulty of finding the solution to GKW becomes clear when the
 search leads one to start discovering complicated identities, such as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{m=1}^{\infty}\,\frac{1}{m^{2}}\psi^{(1)}\left(1+\frac{1}{m}+x\right)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\,\frac{1}{(n+x)^{2}}\psi^{(1)}\left(\frac{1}{n+x}+1\right)\]

\end_inset

or to finding curiosities such as 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=(1+ax)^{2}$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}f=\psi^{(1)}(1+x+a)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=(1+nx)^{-2}-1$
\end_inset

 one gets 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}f=-\sum_{k=1}^{n}(x+k)^{-2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Acting on a general power, the map gives the Hurwitz Zeta: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}x^{s}\right](x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\,\frac{1}{(n+x)^{s+2}}=\zeta_{H}(s+2,x+1)\]

\end_inset

This allows eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
