\begin_layout Standard
This function has many interesting properties and symmetries
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vep-mink2008,Ve-L06,Ve-M04"

\end_inset

.
 The self-symmetry of the curve is generated by two relations, a halving:
 
\begin_inset Formula \[
?\left(\frac{x}{1+x}\right)=\frac{?\left(x\right)}{2}\]

\end_inset

and a left-right reflection: 
\begin_inset Formula $?\left(1-x\right)=1-?\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The full set of symmetries, generating the dyadic monoid, can be exhibited
 by defining 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g_{C}\left(x\right)=\frac{x}{1+x}\mbox{\quad and }\quad g_{D}\left(x\right)=\frac{x}{2}\label{eq:monoid generator g}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and noting that the symmetry relation above may be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $?\circ g_{C}=g_{D}\circ?$
\end_inset

.
 Likewise, letting 
\begin_inset Formula $r\left(x\right)=1-x$
\end_inset

 one has 
\begin_inset Formula $?\circ r=r\circ?$
\end_inset

.
 These two functions can be taken as the generators of a monoid, whose general
 element is written as 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{m}\circ r\circ g^{n}\circ r\circ g^{p}\circ\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 This monoid forms an interesting subset of the modular group 
\begin_inset Formula $SL(2,\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset

.
 Elements of the monoid are in 1-1 correspondance with the Cantor set; alternate
ly, they are in 1-1 correspondance with the binary tree.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the above definitions, one may now derive various identities.
 Thus, one has 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{h}[(1+?(x))/(1+x)^{2}]=1-?(x)\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{h}[?(x)\, x^{-2}]=2-?(x)\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{h}\left[?(x)\left(\frac{1}{(1+x)^{2}}-2\right)\right]=\frac{?(x)-2}{(1+x)^{2}}\]

\end_inset

One may continue in this vein indefinitely, but this exercise does not seem
 to lead to any sort of worthwhile recurrence relations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The generating function for the moments of the Minkowski Question Mark
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Alkauskas2007,Alkauskas2007a,Alkauskas2008"

\end_inset

 participates in a curious identity.
 This generating function obeys the relation 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{1}{z^{2}}G\left(\frac{1}{z}\right)+\frac{1}{\left(z+1\right)^{2}}G\left(\frac{1}{z+1}\right)=\frac{1}{z\left(z+1\right)}\]

\end_inset

which holds for complex-valued 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 (such as, for example, 
\begin_inset Formula $z\mapsto z+n$
\end_inset

), and also 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{1}{z}+\frac{1}{z^{2}}G\left(\frac{1}{z}\right)=G\left(z\right)-2G\left(z+1\right)\]

\end_inset

From this, one has the curious shift-over-by-one relationship 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}G\right]\left(z\right)=G\left(1+z\right)+\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}K\right]\left(z\right)\]

\end_inset

where we've defined 
\begin_inset Formula $K\left(z\right)=G\left(1+z\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can define an object that behaves like the derivative of the Question
 Mark function; properly speaking, it is a singular measure on the unit
 interval.
 For all practical purposes, it can be called the derivative; and it does
 have one surprising property: it is an eigenvector of the GKW, corresponding
 to eigenvalue 1.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{h}?^{\prime}=?^{\prime}\]

\end_inset

A proof of this relation, including all the required machinery to define
 and demonstrate this result, is given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vep-mink2008"

\end_inset

.
 In simple terms, it follows from the self-symmetry relation on the Question
 Mark: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(?\circ g_{C}^{n-1}\circ r\circ g_{C}\right)\left(x\right)=?\left(\frac{1}{n+x}\right)=\frac{1}{2^{n-1}}-\frac{?\left(x\right)}{2^{n}}=\left(g_{D}^{n-1}\circ r\circ g_{D}\circ?\right)\left(x\right)\]

\end_inset

 which induces a relation on the measure:
\begin_inset Formula \[
?^{\prime}\left(\frac{1}{n+x}\right)=\frac{\left(x+n\right)^{2}}{2^{n}}?^{\prime}\left(x\right)\]

\end_inset

This last is easily inserted into the definition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:sum-form"

\end_inset

 to obtain the desired result.
 A graph of the measure is shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Derivative-?"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Miscellaneous Series
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Algebraic manipulations of the above algebraic relations leads one to consider
 various conditionally convergent series, such as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\,(-)^{k}\,\left(\begin{array}{c}
k+m+1\\
m\end{array}\right)\zeta(k+m+2)=1\]

\end_inset

which holds for any integer 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 Additional series, similar to the form given above, are possible, and are
 reported in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vep-A&S-Anno"

\end_inset

.
 Thus, for example, one has:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\,(-)^{k}\,\left(\begin{array}{c}
k+m+1\\
m+1\end{array}\right)\zeta(k+m+2)=\zeta(m+2)-1\]

\end_inset

There are also divergent series which can be evaluated by regulating them,
 and then taking the limit.
 Examples include 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\,(-)^{k}e^{-tk}=\frac{1}{2}\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\,(-)^{k}(k+2)e^{-tk}=\frac{3}{4}\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\,(-)^{k}(k+2)(k+3)e^{-tk}=\frac{7}{4}\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\,(-)^{k}(k+2)(k+3)(k+4)e^{-tk}=\frac{45}{8}\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\,(-)^{k}(k+2)(k+3)(k+4)(k+5)e^{-tk}=\frac{93}{4}\]

\end_inset

These are readily obtained
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Crowley2010"

\end_inset

 by considering the binomial generating function.
 That is, define 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
A_{m}\left(x\right)= & \sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{\Gamma\left(k+m+2\right)}{\Gamma\left(k+2\right)}\left(-x\right)^{k}\\
= & -\frac{\Gamma\left(m+1\right)}{x}\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}{k \choose m}\left(-x\right)^{k}\\
= & \frac{\Gamma\left(m+1\right)}{x}\left(1-\frac{1}{\left(1+x\right)^{m+1}}\right)\end{align*}

\end_inset

and so the above sums are given by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
A_{m}\equiv\lim_{x\to1}A_{m}\left(x\right)=\Gamma\left(m+1\right)\left(\frac{2^{m+1}-1}{2^{m+1}}\right)\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, let
\begin_inset Formula \[
S_{m}\left(x\right)=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\,(-)^{k}\frac{(k+m+1)!}{(k+1)!}\left[\zeta(k+m+2)-1\right]x^{k}\]

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \[
S_{m}\equiv\lim_{x\rightarrow1}S_{m}\left(x\right)\]

\end_inset

then one finds that 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}=1/2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}=1/4$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{2}=1/4$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{3}=3/8$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{4}=3/4$
\end_inset

; the general expression is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{m}=\Gamma\left(m+1\right)/2^{m+1}$
\end_inset

.
 This result can be obtained by simply by examining the zeroth eigenvector
 of the GKW operator, as given below, in equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:GKW-matrix-elts"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eigen-eqn"

\end_inset

.
 Alternately, the general expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{m}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 can be obtained by working with the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}x^{k}$
\end_inset

 (XXX do this and provide expression).
 The above sums appear when considering 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\psi(1+z)=\frac{-1}{1+z}+1-\gamma+\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}(-)^{m}\left[\zeta(m+2)-1\right]z^{m+1}\]

\end_inset

 and then writing 
\begin_inset Formula \[
z^{m+1}=(z+1-1)^{m+1}=\sum_{k=0}^{m}(-)^{m-k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
m\\
k\end{array}\right)(z+1)^{k}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Polynomial Representation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Polynomial-Representation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can attempt to solve GKW by working in the polynomial representation.
 One possible choice is to make one's Taylor expansion about 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

, but this turns out to be a very poor choice.
 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}f=g$
\end_inset

 and substituting a Taylor's expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, so that
\begin_inset Formula \[
f(x)=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{x^{k}}{k!}f^{(k)}(0)\]

\end_inset

and likewise for 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

, one gets 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{g^{(m)}(0)}{m!}=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{f^{(k)}(0)}{k!}\,(-)^{m}\;\frac{(k+m+1)!}{m!\,(k+1)!}\,\zeta(k+m+2)\]

\end_inset

or, adopting the bra-ket notation introduced earlier
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ve-B04"

\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left\langle m\left|\mathcal{L}_{h}\right|k\right\rangle =(-)^{m}\;\left(\begin{array}{c}
k+m+1\\
m\end{array}\right)\,\zeta(k+m+2)\]

\end_inset

where we've replaced the factorials by the binomial coefficient that they
 form.
 Unfortunately, this is clearly a very poorly conditioned matrix.
 One can make some progress, if one wishes, by applying a regulator and
 using Levin-type sequence acceleration techniques.
 One can thus find a number of curious identities, some of which we've listed
 previously.
 However, the difficulty of working with divergent sums seems to outweigh
 any advantages given by the relatively simple form of the matrix elements.
 Thus, one is lead to consider the matrix elements for a polynomial expansion
 about 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

.
 These are far more complex, but give a very well-conditioned matrix.
 These are: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
G_{mn}=\sum_{k=0}^{n}(-)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
k+m+1\\
m\end{array}\right)\,\left[\zeta(k+m+2)-1\right]\label{eq:GKW-matrix-elts}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula \[
(-)^{m}\frac{g^{(m)}(1)}{m!}=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}G_{mn}(-)^{n}\frac{f^{(n)}(1)}{n!}\]

\end_inset

Other authors have chosen to expand about 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1/2$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Briggs2003"

\end_inset

 but it would appear that expansion about 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

 leads to the simplest tractable expansion.
 The general case, of a Taylor's expansion about some fixed point, is explored
 in appendix A.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The eigenvector equation to be solved is then 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}G_{mn}v_{n}=\lambda v_{m}\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $v=\{v_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector with components 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 This beast has a discrete spectrum (XXX need reference for proof), and
 so we may label the eigenvalues and eigenvectors with a label 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, so that the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th eigen equation is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}G_{mn}v_{nk}=\lambda_{k}v_{mk}\label{eq:eigen-eqn}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th polynomial eigenfunction of the GKW operator is then given by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\rho_{k}(x)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}v_{nk}(1-x)^{k}\]

\end_inset

The zeroth eigenfunction was given by Gauss as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\rho_{0}(x)=\frac{1}{1+x}\]

\end_inset

and corresponds to the eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{n0}=2^{-n}$
\end_inset

.
 Again, note the curious appearance of powers of two.
 The zeroth eigenvalue is 1, the first eigenvalue is known as the GKW constant,
 and is about 0.3036.
 Additional eigenvalues are given in table 
