\begin_layout Standard
We have the identity
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}G_{mn}p^{-n}=p\left[\zeta(m+1)-1-\zeta_{H}\left(m+1,2+\frac{1}{p-1}\right)\right]\]

\end_inset

In particular, for 
\begin_inset Formula $p=2$
\end_inset

, the right hand side equals 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{-m}$
\end_inset

; this corresponds to the known eigenvector.
 Note that for any value of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, the leading term on the right is 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{-(m+1)}$
\end_inset

.
 A simple way to arrive at this is to note that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}p^{-n}(1-x)^{n}=\frac{p}{p-1+x}\]

\end_inset

and then evaluate this expression under the action of the GKW operator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Kernel
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The spectrum of the polynomial eigenfunctions of the GKW operator is discrete,
 and does not include zero.
 However, if one considers a larger set of functions, say, the set of square-int
egrable functions, then the spectrum becomes continuous, and includes zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The kernel of the GKW operator is defined as the set of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}f=0$
\end_inset

.
 The kernel of the GKW is readily demonstrated: let 
\begin_inset Formula \[
k_{n}(x)=\begin{cases}
0 & \;\mbox{ for }\;0\le x<\frac{1}{n+2}\\
\frac{1}{x^{2}} & \;\mbox{ for }\;\frac{1}{n+2}\le x<\frac{1}{n+1}\\
\frac{-1}{x^{2}} & \;\mbox{ for }\;\frac{1}{n+1}\le x<\frac{1}{n}\\
0 & \;\mbox{ for }\;\frac{1}{n}\le x\le1\end{cases}\]

\end_inset

Then clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}k_{n}\right](x)=0$
\end_inset

 for all integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n\ge1$
\end_inset

.
 The kernel is in fact much larger.
 Consider the set of functions
\begin_inset Formula \[
c_{n,l}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
0 & \;\mbox{ for }\;0\le x<\frac{1}{n+2}\\
\frac{\cos\left(\left(2l+1\right)\pi/x\right)}{x^{2}} & \;\mbox{ for }\;\frac{1}{n+2}\le x<\frac{1}{n}\\
0 & \;\mbox{ for }\;\frac{1}{n}\le x\le1\end{cases}\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}c_{n,l}\right](x)=\cos\left(\left(2l+1\right)\pi\left(x+n\right)\right)+\cos\left(\left(2l+1\right)\pi\left(x+n+1\right)\right)=0\]

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{n,l}$
\end_inset

 belongs to the kernel for all integer 
\begin_inset Formula $l\ge1$
\end_inset

, as does 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{n,l}$
\end_inset

 when defined analogously for sine instead of cosine.
 
