\begin_layout Subsection
Asymptotic Expansion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The asymptotic behaviour of the matrix elements for large 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n$
\end_inset

 can be obtained by converting the Newton series 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:GKW-matrix-elts"

\end_inset

 to N√∂rlund‚ÄìRice integral, and then using saddle-point methods to obtain
 the large 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n$
\end_inset

 behaviour.
 A detailed exposition of this proceedure is given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Fla06"

\end_inset

; what follows is an abbreviated application of those techniques.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several key steps to this process.
 The first is the observation that a Newton series can be re-written as
 a N√∂rlund‚ÄìRice integral
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Fla94"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{k=n_{0}}^{n}\left(-1\right)^{k}{n \choose k}\phi\left(k\right)=\frac{\left(-1\right)^{n}}{2\pi i}\oint_{c}\phi\left(s\right)\frac{n!}{s\left(s-1\right)\cdots\left(s-n\right)}ds\]

\end_inset

 where the contour 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 surrounds the poles at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ n_{0},\cdots,n\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(s\right)$
\end_inset

 is holomorphic in the region 
\begin_inset Formula $\Re s>n_{0}-\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Substitution of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:GKW-matrix-elts"

\end_inset

 into the above yeilds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
G_{mn}=\frac{\left(-1\right)^{n}}{2\pi i}\frac{n!}{m!}\oint_{C}\frac{\left(s+m+1\right)\left(s+m\right)\cdots\left(s+2\right)}{s\left(s-1\right)\cdots\left(s-n\right)}\left[\zeta\left(s+m+2\right)-1\right]ds\label{eq:gkw-integrand}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Written in this form, the zeros and poles of the integrand are clearly
 evident.
 It also becomes clear that the right-hand closure of the contour integral
 contributes nothing, since, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Re s\to\infty$
\end_inset

, one has that the integrand decays exponentially, 
\emph on
viz
\emph default
.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta\left(s+m+2\right)-1\to2^{-s}+\mathcal{O}\left(3^{-s}\right)$
\end_inset

 which over-powers the polynomial numerator and drives the integrand to
 zero.
 Thus, the closed contour can be replaced by a line integral running from
 
\begin_inset Formula $c-i\infty$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $c+i\infty$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Re c$
\end_inset

 to the left of the poles:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
G_{mn}=\frac{\left(-1\right)^{n+1}}{2\pi i}\frac{\Gamma\left(n+1\right)}{\Gamma\left(m+1\right)}\int_{c-i\infty}^{c+i\infty}\frac{\Gamma\left(s+m+2\right)\Gamma\left(s-n\right)}{\Gamma\left(s+2\right)\Gamma\left(s+1\right)}\left[\zeta\left(s+m+2\right)-1\right]ds\]

\end_inset

The integrand becomes exponentially large for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Re s\to-\infty$
\end_inset

 and this leads to a pair of saddle points above and below the real axis:
 each saddle is situated between the exponential rise to the left and the
 poles, and straddles a hump between the zeros and the exponentially decay
 to the right.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $m=n$
\end_inset

, it will be shown that the saddle points occur at 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\pm in+\mathcal{O}\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The integrand and its saddle points is illustrated in the figure 
