\begin_layout Standard
The integral may be estimated for 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n\to\infty$
\end_inset

 by applying the method of steepest descent.
 That is, one deforms the integration contour so that it passes through
 the saddle-point, following the steepest path through it.
 There, on applies Laplaces method to approximate the integral as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int e^{Nf\left(x\right)}dx=e^{Nf\left(x_{0}\right)}\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{-Nf^{\prime\prime}\left(x_{0}\right)}}\left(1+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{1}{N}\right)\right)\label{eq:steepest descent}\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the integration contour running through the saddle point 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}\left(x_{0}\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 To be able to apply this, the logarithm of the integrand, expanded in powers
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, is required.
 As mentioned, the saddle points will be discovered at 
\begin_inset Formula $s\approx\pm in$
\end_inset

, thus suggesting the change of variable 
\begin_inset Formula $s=nx$
\end_inset

 and an expansion in powers of 
\begin_inset Formula $N=n$
\end_inset

, while holding 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 fixed.
 To avoid a concurrent expansion in powers of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, write 
\begin_inset Formula $m=Kn$
\end_inset

 for some fixed constant 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 One may then proceed with the expansion.
 The zeta function terms expands as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\log\left[\zeta\left(s+m+2\right)-1\right]=-\left[n\left(x+K\right)+2\right]\log2+\mathcal{O}\left(\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^{n\left(x+K\right)}\right)\]

\end_inset

The gamma functions are expanded by applying Stirling's formula, in leading
 powers of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\log\Gamma\left(ny\right)=ny\log\left(ny\right)-ny-\frac{1}{2}\log\left(ny\right)+\frac{1}{2}\log\left(2\pi\right)+\frac{1}{12ny}+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{1}{n^{3}}\right)\]

\end_inset

which is applicable for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Re y>0$
\end_inset

.
 This can be applied in a straightforward way, although to do so, one must
 first write 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Gamma\left(s-n\right)=\frac{\pi\left(-1\right)^{n}}{\sin\left(\pi s\right)\Gamma\left(n-s+1\right)}\]

\end_inset

which follows from the reflection formula 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\left(z\right)\Gamma\left(1-z\right)=\pi/\sin\pi z$
\end_inset

.
 For the saddle point in the upper half-plane, tht is, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Im x>0$
\end_inset

, one expands 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\log\sin\pi xn= & \log\left(\frac{-e^{-i\pi nx}}{2i}+\mathcal{O}\left(e^{-\pi n\Im x}\right)\right)\\
= & -i\pi nx+\frac{i\pi}{2}-\log2+\mathcal{O}\left(e^{-2\pi n\Im x}\right)\end{align*}

\end_inset

Combining all of these elements, one then obtains the following asymptotic
 expansion in 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
Nf\left(x\right)= & n\left(K-1\right)\log n\\
 & +n\left[i\pi x-\left(x+K\right)\log2-2x\log x-\left(1-x\right)\log\left(1-x\right)+\left(K+x\right)\log\left(K+x\right)+1-K\right]\\
 & -\log n\\
 & -2\log x-\frac{1}{2}\log\left(1-x\right)+\frac{3}{2}\log\left(K+x\right)-\log8\pi\\
 & +\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{1}{n}\right)\end{align*}

\end_inset

The first derivative is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
Nf^{\prime}\left(x\right)= & n\left[i\pi-\log2+\log\frac{\left(1-x\right)\left(K+x\right)}{x^{2}}\right]\\
 & +\frac{1}{2\left(1-x\right)}+\frac{3}{2\left(K+x\right)}-\frac{2}{x}+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{1}{n}\right)\end{align*}

\end_inset

while the second derviative is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
Nf^{\prime\prime}\left(x\right)= & n\left[\frac{1}{K+x}-\frac{1}{1-x}-\frac{2}{x}\right]\\
 & +\frac{2}{x^{2}}+\frac{1}{2\left(1-x\right)^{2}}-\frac{3}{2\left(K+x\right)^{2}}+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{1}{n}\right)\end{align*}

\end_inset

Solving for the saddle points 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}\left(x_{0}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
x_{0}=\frac{K-1}{2}\pm\frac{1}{2}\sqrt{1-6K+K^{2}}+\frac{1}{n}\left(\frac{7Kx_{0}-3x_{0}-6K}{2\left(K-x_{0}^{2}\right)}\right)+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{1}{n^{2}}\right)\label{eq:saddle pt}\end{equation}

\end_inset

For the special case of 
\begin_inset Formula $m=n$
\end_inset

, that is 
\begin_inset Formula $K=1$
\end_inset

, one gets the simple form 
\begin_inset Formula \[
x_{0,m=n}=\pm i+\frac{1}{n}\left(\frac{-3}{2}\pm i\right)+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{1}{n^{2}}\right)\]

\end_inset

To obtain asymptotic expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{mn}$
\end_inset

, it is now enough to insert the saddle point 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:saddle pt"

\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:steepest descent"

\end_inset

.
 The algebra is considerably simplified by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $K=1$
\end_inset

.
 The final result is precisely that already discovered numerically: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
G_{nn}=\frac{1}{2^{n+1}\sqrt{\pi n}}\sin\frac{\pi}{2}\left(n+\frac{1}{2}\right)\left[1+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{1}{n}\right)\right]\]

\end_inset

This is an exact, analytic result for the asymptotic expansion of the GKW
 matrix elements as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

, obtained by using the method of steepest descent applied to the N√∂rlund‚ÄìRice
 integral of the Newton series of the GKW operator matrix elements 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:GKW-matrix-elts"

\end_inset

.
