\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Gauss map 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)=\frac{1}{x}-\left\lfloor \frac{1}{x}\right\rfloor $
\end_inset

 has a distinctive sawtooth shape; the transfer operator of the Gauss map
 is the GKW operator.
 This section presents the harmonic sawtooth, which resembles the Gauss
 map, but with stright-line edges.
 The goal here is to develop a model for the GKW, in order to better understand
 it.
 In this case.
 the transfer operator is considerably simpler than GKW; it is solvable.
 The spectrum is similar, in that it is a countable, discrete set of values,
 but is otherwise inequivalent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The harmonic sawtooth uses straight lines arranged between values of 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n$
\end_inset

