\begin_layout Subsection
Relation to the Rieman Zeta function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The harmonic spacing of the sawtooth edges implies that the harmoic sawtooth
 will be related to the Rieman zeta in much the same way as the Gauss map
 is.
 Specifically, the Mellin transofrm gives:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\zeta\left(s\right)=\frac{s+1}{s-1}\left[1-s\int_{0}^{1}w\left(x\right)x^{s-1}dx\right]\]

\end_inset

The above can be obtained in a very straightforward manner by direct substitutio
n.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Polynomial Eigenfunctions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The polynomial eigenfunctions can be obtained in a straight-forward manner,
 by means of Taylor's expansion.
 Expanding 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 as a Taylor's expansion about 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f(x)=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{f^{(k)}(0)}{k!}x^{k}\]

\end_inset

and likewise 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{w}f\right](x)=\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}\frac{g^{\left(m\right)}\left(0\right)}{m!}x^{m}=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n(n+1)}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{f^{(k)}(0)}{k!}\left(\frac{n+1-x}{n(n+1)}\right)^{k}\]

\end_inset

Rearranging the sums, and equating terms with the same power of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, on obtains matrix elements 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{mk}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{g^{\left(m\right)}\left(0\right)}{m!}=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}W_{mk}\frac{f^{(k)}(0)}{k!}\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula \[
W_{mk}=\left\{ \begin{array}{ccc}
\left(-1\right)^{m}\left(\begin{array}{c}
k\\
m\end{array}\right)\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}n^{-k-1}(n+1)^{-m-1} & \;\textrm{ for \;} & k\geq m\\
0 & \;\textrm{ for \;} & k<m\end{array}\right.\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{array}{c}
k\\
m\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

 denotes the binomial coefficient.
 This matrix is upper-triangular, and thus has its eigenvalues along the
 diagonal.
 These are 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lambda_{k}=\left(-1\right)^{k}\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n^{k+1}(n+1)^{k+1}}\]

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}=3-2\zeta(2)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta(x)$
\end_inset

 is the Riemann zeta.
 Numerically, one finds that the first few eigenvalues are 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}=-0.289868...$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}=0.130396...$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{3}=-0.0633278...$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{4}=0.031383...$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{5}=-0.0156468...$
\end_inset

 In the limit of large 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, the first term in the summation will dominate, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{k}\to\left(-1\right)^{k}/2^{k+1}$
\end_inset

; the ratio of eigenvalues settles down to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{k}/\lambda_{k+1}\to-2$
\end_inset

 in the limit.
 The alternating sign of the eigenvalues, as well as the ratio of successive
 eigenvalues, is quite unlike the GKW.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)$
\end_inset

 is singular at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

, and this might suggest that a polynomial expansion around a different
 point might be warrented, as it was for the GKW operator.
 However, this is not needed: since the resulting matrix is solvable, a
 transformation to a different point does not offer much, if anything.
 That is, performing the Taylor's expansion about a point other than 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 just amounts to multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 on the left and right by a binomial transform; this will not make 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 somehow 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

more triangular
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

more solvable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 It might be possible to improve numerical stability in this way, but there
 do not seem to be any other gains.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The matrix elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{mk}$
\end_inset

 are easily computed by means of recurrence relations on the indexes 
\begin_inset Formula $m,k$
\end_inset

.
 This is done by defining 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{mk}$
\end_inset

 and observing that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
Z_{mk}=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\left(n+1\right)^{m+1}n^{k+1}}=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{(n+1)^{m}n^{k}}\left[\frac{1}{n}-\frac{1}{n+1}\right]=Z_{m-1,k}-Z_{m,k-1}\]

\end_inset

These recursion relations are bounded on the edges by 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{00}=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{10}=2-\zeta(2)$
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula \[
Z_{m0}=Z_{m-1,0}-\left(\zeta(m+1)-1\right)=1-\sum_{j=1}^{m}\left[\zeta(j+1)-1\right]\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{01}=\zeta(2)-1$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
Z_{0k}=\zeta(k+1)-Z_{0,k-1}=(-)^{k}\left[1+\sum_{j=1}^{k}(-)^{j}\zeta(j+1)\right]\]

\end_inset

From these, one then has 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{mk}=\left(-1\right)^{m}{k \choose m}Z_{mk}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $m\leq k$
\end_inset

 .
 
\end_layout

