\begin_layout Standard
The transfer operator of this function provides a second model of the Gauss-Kuzm
in-Wirsing operator.
 It can be solved exactly; unfortunately, it is not trivially conjugate
 to the GKW operator, as one might naively hope.
 Normally, when there exists a 
\emph on
smooth
\emph default
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\phi^{-1}\circ\beta\circ\phi$
\end_inset

, then there is a similarity transform that connects the transfer operator
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 with that for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, as developed in the appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Similarity-Transforms"

\end_inset

.
 However, the Question Mark function is not smooth.
 With some effort, one can define it's derivative in a rigorous way
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vep-mink2008"

\end_inset

, but one finds that the derivative is continuous no-where -- vanishing
 on the rationals, infinite on 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

most
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 reals.
 The similarity transform is given by the Jacobian 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left(?^{\prime}\circ?^{-1}\right)\left(x\right)\right|$
\end_inset

 of the Question Mark, pictured in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Derivative-?"

\end_inset

 -- which can be seen to be terribly singular.
 Put another way, although the point dynamics of this sawtooth map are completel
y isomorphic to the point dynamics of the Gauss Map, the distribution of
 these orbits, with respect to the natural measure on the unit interval,
 is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 isomorphic by means of any differentiable function.
 The spectra of the associated transfer operators are 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 identical.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, with suitable tools, it is possible to construct functions on the
 Cantor set for which one can obtain similarity transforms which render
 these operators conjugate.
 Insofar as the Cantor set is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

very nearly
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the unit interval, these functions pass ovre to functions on the unit interval,
 and thus allow solutions to the GKW operator to be obtained.
 The development of these tools and thier application take up most of what
 follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transfer operator for the dyadic sawtooth can be easily seen to be 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[\mathcal{L}_{c}f\right](x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{2^{n}}f\left(\frac{2-x}{2^{n}}\right)\label{eq:L_c transfer oper}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The following sections develop this operator in different function spaces.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Polynomial Basis Eigenfunctions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The polynomial eigenfunctions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{c}$
\end_inset

 may be found in the same way as before.
 Write the Taylor's expansion as 
\end_layout

