\begin_inset Formula \[
f\left(x\right)=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{f^{(k)}(0)}{k!}x^{k}\]

\end_inset

and likewise for 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\mathcal{L}_{c}f$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting and matching monomial terms gives 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{g^{(m)}\left(0\right)}{m!}=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}C_{mk}\frac{f^{(k)}\left(0\right)}{k!}\]

\end_inset

where the matrix elements are given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
C_{mk}=\left(-1\right)^{m}\left({k\atop m}\right)\frac{2^{k-m}}{\left(2^{k+1}-1\right)}\label{eq:C_mk mat elts dyadic saw}\end{equation}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $k\ge m$
\end_inset

 and zero otherwise.
 This matrix is upper-triangular and thus solvable.
 Because it is solvable, there is no advantage gained by performing the
 polynomial expansion at points other than 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

; the matrix cannot become 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

more solvable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 A quick exploration at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

 does not suggest that the matrix becomes 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

more diagonal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
