\begin_layout Subsection
The Failure of the Similarity Transform for the Polynomial Basis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under normal circumstances, whenever one has a pair of maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(x)$
\end_inset

 that are conjugate to each other through a smooth, invertible function
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(x)=(\phi\circ\alpha\circ\phi^{-1})(x)$
\end_inset

, then there exists a similarity transform 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\phi}$
\end_inset

 such that the Frobenius-Perron operators are also conjugate; that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}=S_{\phi}\mathcal{L}_{\alpha}S_{\phi}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\phi}^{-1}=S_{\phi^{-1}}$
\end_inset

.
 The transform 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\phi}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\phi}f=\left(f\circ\phi^{-1}\right)/\left|\phi'\circ\phi^{-1}\right|$
\end_inset

, where the prime denotes differentiation: 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi'(x)=d\phi(x)/dx$
\end_inset

.
 A detailed derrivation of this is given in appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Similarity-Transforms"

\end_inset

.
 Since the continued-fraction shift function is conjugate to the sawtooth,
 one might hope that GKW would be conjugate to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{c}$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{c}=S_{?}\mathcal{L}_{h}S_{?}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Unfortunately, the Minkowski Question Mark is highly singular and is not
 traditionally differentiable, and so we cannot build such a similarity
 transform using the polynomial function basis.
 Another way to deduce this is to note that the similarity transform 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\phi}$
\end_inset

, working as an ordinary, bounded operator, normally preserves the eigenvalues
 of a nuclear operator; that is, the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 equal those of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 In the current case, we see trouble in that the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{c}$
\end_inset

 are not those of GKW.
 They are not even 'close', in that for large 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, the ratio of the eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{k}/\lambda_{k+1}$
\end_inset

 tends to -2, whereas, for the GKW, the ratio is 2.61803...
 (the square of golden mean, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Flajolet1995"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Althought the manipulations required to construct eigenfunctions by means
 of similarity transforms break down when one insists on working in the
 polynomial basis, this is not the case if one considers a larger basis
 of functions.
 By properly defining the derivative, one can validly obtain solutions to
 the GKW eigenequation from solutions to the dyadic sawtooth.
 This is developed in the next section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Constructing GKW Eigenfunctions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Constructing-GKW-Eigenfunctions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The manipulations required to define the conjugacy operator that makes GKW
 and the dyadic sawtooth conjugate require manipulation of the derivative
 of the Minkowski question mark function.
 This derivative is not well-defined if one sticks to the natural topology
 on the real number line, but it can be given a precise expression by working
 on the Cantor set.
 Insofar as the Cantor set is in many ways nearly equivalent to the real
 number line, and that there are many operations that can be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

safely
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 carried over from one to the other, one can thus have a workable set of
 tools for operating on an object that, for all 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

practical purposes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 can be identified with the deriviative of the question mark.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The primary theorem and mechanics establishing this is given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vep-mink2008"

\end_inset

, and breifly recapitulated here.
 The Cantor set can be written as the infinite product 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

 of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 of two elements.
 As such, points in this product space are naturally identified with real
 numbers expanded in base-2 or binary -- a real number may be written as
 an infinity long string of zeros and ones.
 So:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
x=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{b_{k}}{2^{k}}\label{eq:binary expansion}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}\in\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th binary digit in the expansion of the real number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 The natural topology for a Cartesian product space is the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

product topology
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; it's open sets are called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cylinder sets
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 For the Cantor set, a basis for the topology is just given by the standard
 Rademacher functions
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Carothers2005"

\end_inset

 of Banach Space theory.
 That is, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

be an infinite string of binary digits; let 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}$
\end_inset

, or, alternately, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{k}$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th digit in this string.
 Consider the set of all possible strings, but with one digit held constant.
 There are two such sets, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
C_{k,0}=\left\{ \sigma\vert\sigma_{k}=0\right\} \quad\mbox{ and }\quad C_{k,1}=\left\{ \sigma\vert\sigma_{k}=1\right\} \]

\end_inset

These two sets are open in the product toplogy, and are complementary: 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{k,0}\cap C_{k,1}=\varnothing$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{k,0}\cup C_{k,1}=\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

.
 The collection of these sets form a basis for the product topology; the
 topology itself is the set of all finite intersections and arbitrary unions
 of these sets.
 It is not hard to see that the indicator functions for these sets are (up
 to a constant) the Rademacher functions.
 Thus, for example: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mbox{id}_{C_{k,0}}\left(x\right)= & \begin{cases}
0 & \;\mbox{ if }b_{k}=1\\
1 & \mbox{\; if }b_{k}=0\end{cases}\\
= & \frac{1+\mbox{sgn}\left(\sin\left(2^{k}\pi x\right)\right)}{2}\end{align*}

\end_inset

is just a square wave.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The open sets of the product topology on the Cantor set form a sigma algebra
 on the real-number line; they are Borel sets, and are suitable for constructing
 measures on the real-number line.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 denote this sigma algebra, and consider a set function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu:\mathcal{A}\to\left[0,\infty\right]$
\end_inset

.
 When this function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 obeys certain properties, such as sigma-additivity, it becomes a measure.
 The above collection of definitions and maps allow the construction of
 a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $?^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 on the unit interval, that, for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

all practical purposes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, behaves as the deriviative of the Minkowski question mark.
 This measure is constructed by considering the one-to-one correspondance
 between the dyadic binary tree and the tree of Farey fractions.
 These trees are identical in structure, and differ only in the labels assigned
 to thier nodes: in the one case, dyadic fractions, and in the other, rationals.
 As they differ only by labels, then the extension theorem for measures
 applies.
 The function that maps the labels from the one tree to the other is just
 the Minkowski question mark; resulting measure is the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $?^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 It is illustrated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Derivative-?"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That this measure deserves to be identified with, or thought of as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

derivative
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the question mark becomes appearent when one switches over to classical
 notation: one has that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{a}^{b}?^{\prime}\left(x\right)dx=?\left(b\right)-?\left(a\right)\]

\end_inset

The above skims over a fair amount of machinery from measure theory; the
 upshot, however, is to defend the use of the simpler, classical notation.
 Thus, in what follows, we will write 
\begin_inset Formula $?^{\prime}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 as if it were well-defined for a real number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 It is not.
 However, by always reverting to the language of measure theory, and always
 working with the cylider sets formed on the Cantor set, and then considering
 a filter of cylinder sets converging to the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:binary expansion"

\end_inset

, then one always has an object 
\begin_inset Formula $?^{\prime}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 that behaves more or less as if it were a classical function, and can be
 more or less safely manipulated as one.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For what follows, the most important property of this measure is that it
 too has a set of self-similarity properties, induced by the action of the
 dyadic monoid on the question mark.
 Of the various self-similarities, the most important one is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
?^{\prime}\left(\frac{1}{n+x}\right)=\frac{\left(x+n\right)^{2}}{2^{n}}?^{\prime}\left(x\right)\]

\end_inset

which follows from 
\begin_inset Formula \[
?\left(\frac{1}{n+x}\right)=\frac{2-?\left(x\right)}{2^{n}}\]

\end_inset

This may be directly employed with the GKW operator to great effect.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is an eigenfuction of the transfer operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{c}$
\end_inset

 of the dyadic sawtooth with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

; that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{c}f=\lambda f$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $q=?^{\prime}\cdot f\circ?$
\end_inset

 is an eigenfunction of the GKW operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}q=\lambda q$
\end_inset

.
 The functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 that can be manipulated in this way are in general functions on the Cantor
 set, and not, strictly speaking, functions on the unit interval, except
 insofar as equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:binary expansion"

\end_inset

 allows the Cantor set and the unit interval to be confused with one-another.
 That is, rather than imagining that 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\left[0,1\right]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, one should instead keep in mind 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\mathbb{N}}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 or even possibly that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a set function on the product topology (equivalently, a set function
 on a sigma algebra), as needed.
 Considered as functions on the unit interval, these will typically be non-diffe
rentiable on the rationals or the dyadic fractions; or they may even be
 discontinuous at these points.
 Although one is tempted to say them, it is important to avoid phrases like
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

differentiable nowhere
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

discontinuous everywhere
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, as these are misleading: the discontinuities happen only on the rationals,
 and the rationals are simply not that big a set.
 Many examples of such eigenfunctions are developed in the sections that
 follow.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By using either a sigma algebra or a topology as the base space for a function
 space, the notion of the transfer operator changes as well.
 That is, when one focuses on point dynamics, then one might define a function
 space as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}=\left\{ f\,\vert\, f:\left[0,1\right]\to\mathbb{R}\right\} $
\end_inset

, that is, as the set of all functions on the unit interval.
 Lets call this space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

 with the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 emphasizing that the base space is a point-set.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ordinary
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 transfer operator is then a map between such spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

, as previously defined.
 However, the measure-theoretic approach instead requires that the function
 space be defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\sigma}=\left\{ f\,\vert\, f:\mathcal{A}\to\mathbb{R}\right\} $
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 is a sigma algebra.
 Here, the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is a reminder that the base space for this 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sigma algebra.
 Note that, in a certain sense, the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

derivatives
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of corresponding elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\sigma}$
\end_inset

, and that the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 is much 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

larger
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 than 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as integrals, over some set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\in\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

, of the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 The elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 are sometimes called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

generalized functions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, in that the Dirac delta function finds a comfortable home there: 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is simply the indicator function for all sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 that contain the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 To relate these two spaces, one then typically uses the language of topological
 filters to establish a many-to-one mapping of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 One curious thing happens to the transfer operator when working with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

: the transfer operator is now nothing more than a pushforward.
 This interpretation gives a nice theoretical grounding; pushforwards are
 fairly well understood category-theoretic objects.
 This preceeding paragraph is again a whirlwind review of some concepts
 from topology and measure theory; more concrete details can be found in
 tectbooks such as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kle08"

\end_inset

, while theorems that recast the transfer operator ass a pushforward are
 given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vep-mink2008,Ve-B04"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Keeping in mind that the proper setting for both the transfer operator and
 for the Minkowski measure 
\begin_inset Formula $?^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 is on sigma algebras, we none-the-less revert to classical point-set notation
 to supply a proof that a similarity transform connects solutions of the
 dyadic sawtooth and the GKW operator:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}?^{\prime}\cdot f\circ?\right]\left(x\right)= & \sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\left(x+n\right)^{2}}?^{\prime}\left(\frac{1}{x+n}\right)\left(f\circ?\right)\left(\frac{1}{x+n}\right)\\
= & ?^{\prime}\left(x\right)\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{2^{n}}f\left(\frac{2-?\left(x\right)}{2^{n}}\right)\\
= & ?^{\prime}\left(x\right)\cdot\left[\mathcal{L}_{c}f\right]\left(?\left(x\right)\right)\\
= & \lambda?^{\prime}\left(x\right)f\left(?\left(x\right)\right)\\
= & \lambda\left(?^{\prime}f\circ?\right)\left(x\right)\end{align*}

\end_inset

The above point-set notation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

works
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, in that, at each step, there is a corresponding measure-theoretic expression
 for which the equality holds.
 Notationally, this classical point-set notation is simply easier to read
 for a wider audience, without loosing the overall fidelity of the argument.
 Given an eigenfunction 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{c}$
\end_inset

, the practical way to work with this will be to work with the quantity
 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{a}^{b}\left(?^{\prime}f\circ?\right)\left(x\right)dx=\int_{?\left(a\right)}^{?\left(b\right)}f\left(y\right)dy\]

\end_inset

The quantity on the left may be understood to denote an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 valued on the set 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\left[a,b\right]\in\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

, while that on the right can be taken as an ordinary, college-calculus
 integral, for which the usual manipulations are allowed.
 Both sides of the above equality are understood to give an eigenfunction
 of the GKW operator.
 In general, this eigenfunction will, in practice, be found to be discontinuous
 on the rationals.
 However, suppose instead one now had not just a single eigenfunction, but
 in fact a complete set of them, spanning a suitable function space.
 One may then ask if there are linear combinations of these that are continuous,
 or even differentiable, with regards to the natural topology on the unit
 interval.
 This last question then spells out the program for the subsequent sections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A practical method for picking out the continuous eigenfunctions out of
 the haystack of all possible eigenfunctions is to look for the bounded
 eigenfunctions.
 Specifically, one would look for those 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 which satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lim_{b-a\to0}\,\frac{1}{b-a}\int_{?\left(a\right)}^{?\left(b\right)}f\left(y\right)dy\,<\infty\]

\end_inset

This is harder than it seems, because, as 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $?\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

 approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $?\left(b\right)$
\end_inset

 exponentially fast when 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 straddle a rational number, while 'staying apart' exponentially fast when
 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 straddle a quadratic irrational.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has to be very 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

badly behaved
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in order for 
\begin_inset Formula $?^{\prime}f\circ?$
\end_inset

 to be well-behaved.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Axiom of Choice
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A few words are in order about the axiom of choice.
 First, recall its definition.
 Given an indexed family of sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ E_{\alpha}\right\} _{\alpha\in A}$
\end_inset

, with each of the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 non-empty, the axiom states that the Cartesian product 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{\alpha\in A}E_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is also non-empty, or more specifically, that one can choose an element
 that belongs to the product.
 If we take each 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 to be the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

, then the Cartesian product can be understood to be a real number; selecting
 a specific real number requires the exercise of the Axiom of Choice.
 Similarly, if we take each 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, then the Cartesian product can be understood as a continued fraction --
 again, a specific point on the real number line.
 By contrast, employing the cylinder set topology can avoid an appeal to
 the Axiom of Choice: to define a cylinder set, one need only pick a finite
 number of explicit elements (which can always be done); the rest of the
 Caretsian product is left indefinite, and does not require an infinite
 number of choices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Kernel of the Dyadic Sawtooth
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The kernel of the dyadic sawtooth is defined as the set of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{c}k=0$
\end_inset

.
 It is clear that none of the polynomial eigenfunctions belong to the kernel;
 the polynomial spectrum is discrete, and zero is not a part of the spectrum.
 However, if one considers a larger set of functions, say the square-integrable
 functions, then the kernel is readily demonstrated.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula \[
k_{n}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
1 & \;\mbox{ for }\;0\le x<\frac{1}{2^{n+1}}\\
-1 & \;\mbox{ for }\;\frac{1}{2^{n+1}}\le x<\frac{1}{2^{n}}\\
0 & \;\mbox{ for }\;\frac{1}{2^{n}}\le x<\infty\end{cases}\]

\end_inset

then clearly one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{c}k_{n}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\ge0$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, each 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{n}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent of the others.
 Note that the 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{n}$
\end_inset

 shift under a doubling of the argument: 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{n}\left(2x\right)=k_{n+1}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

, or alternately, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{n}\circ g_{D}=k_{n-1}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{D}$
\end_inset

 is as defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:monoid generator g"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fractal Eigenfunctions of the Dyadic Sawtooth
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Takagi curve can be used to build an alternate set of eigenfunctions
 for the dyadic sawtooth, possessing continuous-spectrum eigenvalues.
 These eigenfunctions are not differentiable, and thus cannot be obtained
 through polynomials, and thus are not visible when working with the operator
 in a polynomial-basis Hilbert Space.
 They can be used to build an alternate function space, in which the dyadic
 sawtooth remains exactly solvable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Takagi curve has a set of self-similarities generated by the dyadic
 monoid
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ve-T04"

\end_inset

; this monoid was already introduced above, in the paragraph surrounding
 eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:monoid generator g"

\end_inset

.
 One of the elements from the monoid is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[g_{D}^{k-1}r_{D}g_{D}\right](x)=\frac{1}{2^{k-1}}-\frac{x}{2^{k}}\label{eq:argument-as-grg}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and it appears in the definition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:L_c transfer oper"

\end_inset

 of the transfer operator: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{c}f\right](x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{2^{n}}f\left(\left[g_{D}^{n-1}r_{D}g_{D}\right](x)\right)\]

\end_inset

From this, one may surmise that functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 that are self-similar under the dyadic monoid might be used to construct
 solutions to the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{C}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, the candidates are of course the family of Takagi curves.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
