\begin_layout Standard
This curve is self-similar to itself under the dyadic monoid generated by
 the two elements 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 The specific self-similarity is given by a 3-dimensional matrix representation
 of this monoid.
 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{w}$
\end_inset

 as a part of a 3-vector:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
x\\
t_{w}\left(x\right)\end{array}\right)\]

\end_inset

one finds that the monoid acts on the vector with the matrix transformations
 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g_{3}=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \frac{1}{2} & 0\\
0 & 1 & w\end{array}\right)\quad\mbox{ and }\quad r_{3}=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & 0\\
1 & -1 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1\end{array}\right)\label{eq:g_3 matrix}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The self-similarity may be expressed as a monoid action isomorphism: 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{w}\circ g_{D}=g_{3}t_{w}$
\end_inset

 and likewise 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{w}\circ r_{D}=r_{3}t_{w}$
\end_inset

.
 To obtain the behaviour of 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{w}$
\end_inset

 when inserted into eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:L_c transfer oper"

\end_inset

, one needs the action of the element 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{k-1}rg$
\end_inset

 so as to obtain the monoid action isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{w}g_{D}^{k-1}r_{D}g_{D}=g_{3}^{k-1}r_{3}g_{3}t_{w}$
\end_inset

.
 This can be assembled in pieces.
 First, note that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{3}^{n}=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & 2^{-n} & 0\\
0 & \; q_{n}(w)\; & w^{n}\end{array}\right)\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{n}(w)$
\end_inset

 is the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula \[
q_{n}(w)=\frac{1}{2^{n-1}}\sum_{k-0}^{n-1}(2w)^{k}=\frac{1}{2^{n-1}}\left(\frac{1-(2w)^{n}}{1-2w}\right)\]

\end_inset

Multiplying by 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{3}$
\end_inset

and applying to the vector, one obtains 
\begin_inset Formula \[
t_{w}\left(\frac{1}{2^{k-1}}-\frac{x}{2^{k}}\right)=q_{k-1}(w)+x\left(w^{k-1}-q_{k-1}(w)/2\right)+w^{k}t_{w}(x)\]

\end_inset

Inserting the above back into the definition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:L_c transfer oper"

\end_inset

 for the sawtooth operator, and performing the sum, one obtains
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{c}t_{w}\right](x)=\frac{4}{3(2-w)}+\frac{x}{3(2-w)}+\frac{wt_{w}(x)}{2-w}\]

\end_inset

From this, we can immediately read off the eigenvalue as 
\begin_inset Formula $w/(2-w)$
\end_inset

.
 To get the eigenfunction, we need to complete the diagonalization by using
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathcal{L}_{C}1\right](x)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathcal{L}_{C}x\right](x)=(2-x)/3$
\end_inset

 to get the eigenfunction 
\begin_inset Formula \[
E_{2}(x)=\frac{2-w}{2(w+1)(w-1)}+\frac{x}{2(w+1)}+t_{w}(x)\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above is not the only fractal solution that transforms under the three-dimen
sional representation of the dyadic monoid.
 A complete set of linearly independent solutions spanning the space are
 constructed from 
\begin_inset Formula \[
t_{w,l}\left(x\right)=t_{w}\left(\left(2l+1\right)x\right)\]

\end_inset

Theorem: above provide a complete set spanning the space.
 Proof: XXX details to be done.
 Sketch of proof is that these can be re-expressed as unique linear combinations
