\begin_layout Standard
Practical computations with the complete set of fractal eigenfunctions require
 additional tools.
 These are developed here.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is a function posessing dyadic self-similarity, then given 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{D}$
\end_inset

 as some product of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{D}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{D}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 self-similar under the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{f}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{f}$
\end_inset

, then one has the commuting diagram 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{f}f=f\circ\gamma_{D}$
\end_inset

.
 Computations with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{c}$
\end_inset

 require the evaluation of expressions of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\left(2l+1\right)\left(2-x\right)2^{-n}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 If the argument is re-expressed in terms of the transforms 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{D}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{D}$
\end_inset

, analogously to eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:argument-as-grg"

\end_inset

, then one may use the the commutation relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{f}f=f\circ\gamma_{D}$
\end_inset

 to easily compute eigenvectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 This motivates the development of the machinery below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To perform this re-write, it is sufficient to re-express 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(M-y\right)2^{-n}$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{D}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{D}$
\end_inset

.
 We begin by noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(M-y\right)2^{-n}=\left(M-1+r_{D}y\right)2^{-n}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{D}y=1-y$
\end_inset

.
 Next, one needs the binary expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $M-1$
\end_inset

; so write 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
M-1=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\beta_{k}2^{k}\label{eq:M-1-binary-expand}\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{k}\in\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th bit in the base-2 representation.
 Of course, all 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{k}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k>\log_{2}\left(M-1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The desired expression is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{M-y}{2^{n}}=B_{n}B_{n-1}\cdots B_{1}B_{0}r_{D}y\]

\end_inset

where each 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{k}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
B_{k}=\begin{cases}
L & \;\mbox{ for }\beta_{k}=0\\
R & \;\mbox{ for }\beta_{k}=1\end{cases}\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 are left and right sub-trees of the dyadic tree, respectively: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
L\left(x\right)=g_{D}\left(x\right)=\frac{x}{2}\hspace{1em}\mbox{ and }\hspace{1em}R\left(x\right)=\left(r_{D}g_{D}r_{D}\right)\left(x\right)=\frac{1+x}{2}\]

\end_inset

Functions written next to one-another are understood to mean function compositio
n: 
\begin_inset Formula $pqrx=\left(p\circ q\circ r\right)\left(x\right)=p\left(q\left(r\left(x\right)\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 For a fixed value of 
\begin_inset Formula $M-1$
\end_inset

, the transfer operator for the dyaic sawtooth may then be written as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{c}f=\frac{1}{2}f\, B_{0}r+\frac{1}{4}f\, B_{1}B_{0}r+\frac{1}{8}f\, B_{2}B_{1}B_{0}r+\cdots\]

\end_inset

If the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is self-similar under the dyadic monoid, 
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
 if it commutes with 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 then the above provides a convenient, relatively simple way of explicitly
 computing the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
 one has
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{c}f=\left[\frac{1}{2}\, B_{0}r+\frac{1}{4}\, B_{1}B_{0}r+\frac{1}{8}\, B_{2}B_{1}B_{0}r+\cdots\right]f\]

\end_inset

which is straight-forward to evaluate when the 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{k}$
\end_inset

 are square matricies, such as, for example, those of eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g_3 matrix"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several examples can help ground and clarify this.
 Consider, for example 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(6-y\right)/8$
\end_inset

.
 The binary expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $6-1=5$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $101$
\end_inset

