The Cantor function transforms under a two-dimensional representation of
 the dyadic monoid.
 It is constructed from the step function 
\begin_inset Formula \[
b\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
0 & \ \mbox{ for }0\le x<\frac{1}{2}\\
1 & \ \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{2}\le x<1\end{cases}\]

\end_inset

and a weight 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 (equal to 1/3 for the canonical Cantor function):
\begin_inset Formula \[
b_{w}\left(x\right)=\left(1-w\right)\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}w^{n}b\left(2^{n}x-\left\lfloor 2^{n}x\right\rfloor \right)\]

\end_inset

This function is shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Cantor-Function"

\end_inset

.
 It is self-similar under the action of the dyadic monoid: the generators
 are 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{w}\left(x/2\right)=wb_{w}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{w}\left(1-x\right)=1-b_{w}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 As a matrix representation, one has 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
1\to e_{1}= & \left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0\end{array}\right]\\
t_{w}\to e_{2}= & \left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
1\end{array}\right]\end{align*}

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g_{b}= & \left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & w\end{array}\right]\\
r_{b}= & \left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
1 & -1\end{array}\right]\end{align*}

\end_inset

are the generators of the dyadic monoid in this representation.
 Applying the previous developments, one then has that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{c}b_{w}\right]\left(x\right)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{2^{n}}b_{w}\left(\frac{2-x}{2^{n}}\right)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{2^{n}}g_{b}^{n-1}r_{b}g_{b}b_{w}\left(x\right)\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{b}^{n-1}r_{b}g_{b}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
w^{n-1} & -w^{n}\end{array}\right]\]

\end_inset

one promptly obtains that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{c}b_{w}\right]\left(x\right)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{2^{n}}\left(w^{n-1}-w^{n}b_{w}\left(x\right)\right)=\frac{1-wb_{w}\left(x\right)}{2-w}\]

\end_inset

From this, one can then promptly obtain an eigenfunction 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{w}=b_{w}-1/2$
\end_inset

 which satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{c}e_{w}=\frac{-w}{2-w}e_{w}\]

\end_inset

Additional eigenfunctions transforming according to the same representation
 are given by 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{w,l}\left(x\right)=b_{w}\left(\left(2l+1\right)x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Applying the techniques above, one finds that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{c}b_{w,l}=\frac{1}{2-w}c_{w,l}-\frac{w}{2-w}b_{w,l}\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{w,l}$
\end_inset

 is a piecewise-constant depending on 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 .
 Eigenfunctions are then given by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
e_{w,l}=\frac{-c_{w,l}}{2}+b_{w,l}\]

\end_inset

which satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{c}e_{w,l}=\frac{-w}{2-w}e_{w,l}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We've already seen that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{w,0}=1$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $l=1,$
\end_inset

 one has
\begin_inset Formula \[
c_{w,1}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
\frac{5-w}{4} & \quad\mbox{ for }0\le x<\frac{1}{3}\\
\frac{1+3w}{4} & \quad\mbox{ for }\frac{1}{3}\le x<\frac{2}{3}\\
\frac{3-w}{2} & \quad\mbox{ for }\frac{2}{3}\le x<1\end{cases}\]

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $l=2$
\end_inset

 one has 
\begin_inset Formula \[
c_{w,2}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
\frac{9-w}{8} & \quad\mbox{ for }0\le x<\frac{1}{5}\\
\frac{1+7w}{8} & \quad\mbox{ for }\frac{1}{5}\le x<\frac{2}{5}\\
\frac{7-3w}{4} & \quad\mbox{ for }\frac{2}{5}\le x<\frac{3}{5}\\
\frac{3+w}{4} & \quad\mbox{ for }\frac{3}{5}\le x<\frac{4}{5}\\
\frac{5-w}{4} & \quad\mbox{ for }\frac{4}{5}\le x<1\end{cases}\]

\end_inset

The general expression is given by thie piece-wise flat function 
\begin_inset Formula \[
c_{w,l}\left(x\right)=w+\left(1-w\right)\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{\beta_{k}}{2^{k}}\quad\mbox{ for }\frac{4l+1-\left(M-1\right)}{2l+1}\le x<\frac{4l+2-\left(M-2\right)}{2l+1}\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M-1$
\end_inset

 and the binary bits 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{k}$
\end_inset

 are related as given in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:M-1-binary-expand"

\end_inset

.
 The above formula may be derived by applying the techniques from section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Practical Tools"

\end_inset

, commuting so as to use the 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matricies 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{b}=g_{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{b}=r_{b}g_{b}r_{b}$
\end_inset

, and expanding in powers of 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

, and tracking each power separately.
 Note that the sum has the effect of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reversing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the order of the bits in the binary expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $M-1$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}c_{w,l}\left(x\right)dx=2l+1$
\end_inset

.
 In computing the above, it is useful to have a certain polynomial: let
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 be a product of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\gamma=L^{m_{0}}R^{m_{1}}L^{m_{2}}\cdots L^{m_{N-1}}R^{m_{N}}\]

\end_inset

Then one has that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\gamma_{b}\left(w\right)=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
q_{\gamma}\left(w\right) & w^{M}\end{array}\right]\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M=m_{0}+m_{1}+\cdots+m_{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

is the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula \[
q_{\gamma}\left(w\right)=w^{m_{0}}-w^{m_{0}+m_{1}}+w^{m_{0}+m_{1}+m_{2}}-\cdots+\left(-1\right)^{N}w^{M}\]

\end_inset

Since the 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{k}$
\end_inset

 are counting the number of repeated digits in a binary expansion, we once
 again see the insiduous presence of integer series (and thus the connection
 to continued fractions, these being given by integer series).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The three dimensional representation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As noted above, the Takagi curve transforms under a 3D representation of
 the dyadic monoid.
 A few more factoids about this are below.
 Under the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{c}$
\end_inset

, the Takagi curves transform as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{c}t_{w,l}\right]\left(x\right)=\frac{1}{2-w}\left[\alpha_{l}\left(w\right)+x\beta_{l}\left(w\right)+wt_{w,l}\left(x\right)\right]\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{l}\left(w\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{l}\left(w\right)$
\end_inset

 are polynomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $l=0$
\end_inset

 case was already given above; for 
\begin_inset Formula $l=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le x<1/3$
\end_inset

, one has 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\alpha_{1}\left(w\right)=\frac{3}{4}\;\mbox{ and }\;\beta_{1}\left(w\right)=\frac{19}{24}\]

\end_inset

which is obtained using the methods above.
 The correspoding eigenfunctions are given by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
E_{w,l}\left(x\right)=\frac{-1}{1-w}\left[\frac{\alpha_{l}\left(w\right)}{2}+\frac{1}{3}\right]+x\,\frac{3}{2}\,\frac{\beta_{l}\left(w\right)}{1+w}+t_{w,l}\left(x\right)\]

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{c}E_{w,l}\right]\left(x\right)=\frac{w}{2-w}E_{w,l}\left(x\right)\]

\end_inset

Since the eigenvalue is 
\begin_inset Formula $w/\left(2-w\right)$
\end_inset

 as before, the general solution may be written as a linear combination
 of these solutions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Previously, we saw that the Takagi Curves served as basis vectors for a
 space of degenerate eigenfunctions of the Bernoulli Map, associated with
 arbitrary eigenvalue.
 We saw that this space could also be spanned by the Hurwitz Zeta, through
 a change of basis.
 Thus, we expect that we can extend these results to this map as well.
 That is, there is a linear combination of the 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{w,l}$
\end_inset

 that is differentiable in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Walsh functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Walsh functions provide an orthonormal basis for the Banach space 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 of square-integrable functions on tthe unit interval.
 These can be used to construct eigensolutions to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 This section defines the Walsh functions, and constructs a set of self-similar
 functions from them, transforming under a finite-dimensional representation
 of the dyadic monoid.
 These are in turn used to construct the eigensolutions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Walsh functions are built from the Rademacher functions.
 Define the step function 
\begin_inset Formula \[
s_{1}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
+1 & \;\mbox{ for }0\le x<\frac{1}{2}\\
-1 & \;\mbox{ for }\frac{1}{2}\le x\le1\end{cases}\]

\end_inset

and extend it to the whole real-number line by making it be periodic (
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
 so that its a square wave).
 The Rademacher functions 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 are defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}\left(x\right)=s_{1}\left(2^{n}x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Given a finite sequence of positive integers 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}<n_{2}<n_{3}<\cdots<n_{k}$
\end_inset

, the corresponding Walsh function is defined as the product of Rademacher
 functions 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n_{1}}r_{n_{2}}r_{n_{3}}\cdots r_{n_{k}}$
\end_inset

.
 It is not hard to see that these are orthonormal on the unit interval;
 indeed, the 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}$
\end_inset

 themselves are orthonormal, in that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{0}^{1}r_{m}\left(x\right)r_{n}\left(x\right)dx=\delta_{nm}\]

\end_inset

These may be paramterized by means of an integer.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 be an integer with the binary expansion
\begin_inset Formula \[
m=\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\beta_{k}2^{k-1}\]

\end_inset

with each 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{k}\in\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Implicit is that there is some upper bound 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 above which all the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{k}$
\end_inset

 are zero.
 Then define the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

'th Walsh function 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{m}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
s_{m}\left(x\right)=\prod_{k=0}^{\infty}r_{k}^{\beta_{k}}\left(x\right)\]

\end_inset

In essence, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{k}=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{k}$
\end_inset

 appears in the product; if 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{k}=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{k}$
\end_inset

 does not.
 These are orthonormal, in that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{m}^{2}=1$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{0}^{1}s_{m}\left(x\right)s_{n}\left(x\right)dx=\delta_{nm}\]

\end_inset

and these form a complete basis for the space of square-integrable functions
 on the unit interval
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Carothers2005"

\end_inset

.
 The Walsh functions have many curious properties; among those relevant
 here are that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{m}\left(2x\right)=s_{2m}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{m}s_{n}=s_{m\oplus n}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $m\oplus n$
\end_inset

 denotes the bitwise XOR of the binary expansion of the two integers 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{0}(x)=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 That is, the non-negative integers form an abelian group under bitwise
 XOR, and the Walsh functions are isomorphic, as a group, under multiplication.
 A sampling of these functions are shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Walsh-Functions"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

