\begin_layout Standard
A set of fractal functions, corresponding 1-1 to the Walsh functions, and
 transforming under the dyadic monoid, are built as usual.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\rho_{m}\left(x\right)=\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}w^{j}s_{m}\left(2^{j}x\right)\]

\end_inset

It is not hard to see that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\rho_{m}\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)=s_{\left\lfloor \frac{m}{2}\right\rfloor }\left(x\right)+w\rho_{m}\left(x\right)\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\lfloor v\right\rfloor $
\end_inset

 denotes the floor of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 (largest integer less than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

).
 Under the action of reflection 
\begin_inset Formula $r\left(x\right)=1-x$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{m}$
\end_inset

 is even or odd, depending on whther the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 bits in 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is even or odd.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be the smallest integer such that 
\begin_inset Formula $m<2^{N}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the length, in bits, of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, ignoring the infinite string of zero bits to the leftq).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{m}$
\end_inset

 transforms under an 
\begin_inset Formula $N+1$
\end_inset

 dimensional representation of the dyadic monoid, given by the basis
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
1 & \to e_{1}\\
s_{\left\lfloor \frac{m}{2^{N-1}}\right\rfloor } & \to e_{2}\\
s_{\left\lfloor \frac{m}{2^{N-2}}\right\rfloor } & \to e_{3}\\
 & \cdots\\
s_{\left\lfloor \frac{m}{2}\right\rfloor } & \to e_{N}\\
\rho_{m} & \to e_{N+1}\end{align*}

\end_inset

In this basis, the two monoid generators are 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g=\left[\begin{array}{cccccc}
1 & 0 & 0 & \cdots & 0 & 0\\
1 & 0 & 0 & \cdots & 0 & 0\\
0 & 1 & 0 & \cdots & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1 & \cdots & 0 & 0\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots &  & \vdots & \vdots\\
0 & 0 & 0 & \cdots & 1 & w\end{array}\right]\quad\mbox{ and }\quad r=\left[\begin{array}{cccccc}
1 & 0 & 0 & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
0 & \sigma_{1} & 0 & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
0 & 0 & \sigma_{2} & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
0 & 0 & 0 & \sigma_{3} & \cdots & 0\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots &  & \vdots\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 0 & \cdots & \sigma_{N}\end{array}\right]\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{k}=\pm1$
\end_inset

 depending on the number of 1 bits in the binary expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\lfloor m/2^{N-k}\right\rfloor $
\end_inset

.
 To be precise, let 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{k}=\sum_{j=N-k+1}^{N}\beta_{j}$
\end_inset

 count the number of 1 bits in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\lfloor m/2^{N-k}\right\rfloor $
\end_inset

; then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{k}=\left(-1\right)^{c_{k}}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{1}=-1$
\end_inset

 always.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To obtain the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{c}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{m}$
\end_inset

, one needs an expression for the matrix elements 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{n-1}rg$
\end_inset

.
 These are easily obtained, because of the simple, bi-diagonal, shift form
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 The most relevant one, for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\ge N$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g^{n-1}rg=\left[\begin{array}{ccccccc}
1 & 0 &  &  & \vdots\\
1 & 0 &  & \cdots & 0 & \cdots\\
1 & 0 &  &  & \vdots\\
\vdots & \vdots\\
1 & 0 & 0 & \cdots & 0 & 0 & 0\\
p_{n-N}\left(w\right) & \sigma_{2}w^{n-N+1} & \sigma_{3}w^{n-N+2} & \cdots & \sigma_{N-1}w^{n-2} & \sigma_{N}w^{n-1} & \sigma_{N}w^{n}\end{array}\right]\]

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{k}$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{k}\left(w\right)=\left(1-2w^{k}+w^{k+1}\right)/\left(1-w\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}\left(w\right)=1-w$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}\left(w\right)=-1$
\end_inset

.
 It is given by the recurrence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{k+1}=1+wp_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Making use of the property that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{p_{n-N}\left(w\right)}{2^{n}}=0\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, one can find that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{c}\rho_{m}=\frac{1}{2-w}\left(\frac{\sigma_{2}s_{1}}{2^{N-2}}+\frac{\sigma_{3}s_{m_{2}}}{2^{N-3}}+\frac{\sigma_{4}s_{m_{3}}}{2^{N-4}}+\cdots+\frac{\sigma_{N-1}s_{m_{N-2}}}{2}+\sigma_{N}s_{m_{N-1}}+\sigma_{N}w\rho_{m}\right)\]

\end_inset

Here, we've made use of the notation 
\begin_inset Formula \[
m_{k}=\left\lfloor \frac{m}{2^{N-k}}\right\rfloor =\sum_{j=N-k+1}^{N}\beta_{j}2^{j-N+k-1}=m\gg\left(N-k\right)\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gg$
\end_inset

 denotes the bit shift-right operator.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{N}=m$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}=1$
\end_inset

 always.
 
\end_layout

