\begin_layout Standard
From the above, it is immediately clear that eigenfunctions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{c}$
\end_inset

 can be constructed from linear combinations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{m}$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{m_{k}}$
\end_inset

, and that the eigenvalues will be 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{N}w/\left(2-w\right)$
\end_inset

.
 To obtain these, one needs the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{c}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 This is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{c}s_{m}=\sigma_{N}\frac{s_{m_{N-1}}}{2}+\sigma_{N-1}\frac{s_{m_{N-2}}}{4}+\cdots+\sigma_{2}\frac{s_{m_{1}}}{2^{N-1}}=\sum_{k=1}^{N-1}\sigma_{k+1}\frac{s_{m_{k}}}{2^{N-k}}\]

\end_inset

The eigen-equation is then 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{c}v_{m}=\lambda_{m}v_{m}\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{m}=\sigma_{N}w/\left(2-w\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
v_{m}\left(x\right)=\rho_{m}\left(x\right)+\sum_{k=1}^{N-1}a_{k}s_{m_{k}}\left(x\right)\label{eq:dyadic-walsh-eigenfunc}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here, the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

 are just numbers, and are given by a recurrence relation: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
a_{N-k}=\frac{\sigma_{N}\sigma_{N-k+1}}{2^{k-1}w}\left[1+\left(2-w\right)\sum_{j=1}^{k-1}2^{j-1}a_{N-j}\right]\label{eq:walsh-a_k}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The first few of these are 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
a_{N-1} & =\frac{1}{w}\\
a_{N-2} & =\frac{\sigma_{N}\sigma_{N-1}}{w^{2}}\\
a_{N-3} & =\frac{\sigma_{N-2}}{w^{3}}\left[\sigma_{N-1}+\frac{w}{2}\left(\sigma_{N}-\sigma_{N-1}\right)\right]\end{align*}

\end_inset

and, written inthis 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reduced
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 way, these expressions become progressively more complicated.
 The coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

