\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, is shown in the graph 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Coefficient-a1"

\end_inset

.
 Putting this all together, the first few eigenfunctions are 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
v_{1}\left(x\right) & =\rho_{1}\left(x\right)\\
v_{2}\left(x\right) & =\frac{s_{1}\left(x\right)}{w}+\rho_{2}\left(x\right)\\
v_{3}\left(x\right) & =\frac{s_{1}\left(x\right)}{w}+\rho_{3}\left(x\right)\\
v_{4}\left(x\right) & =\frac{s_{1}\left(x\right)}{w^{2}}+\frac{s_{2}\left(x\right)}{w}+\rho_{4}\left(x\right)\\
v_{5}\left(x\right) & =\frac{-s_{1}\left(x\right)}{w^{2}}+\frac{s_{2}\left(x\right)}{w}+\rho_{5}\left(x\right)\\
v_{6}\left(x\right) & =\frac{s_{1}\left(x\right)}{w^{2}}+\frac{s_{3}\left(x\right)}{w}+\rho_{6}\left(x\right)\\
v_{7}\left(x\right) & =\frac{-s_{1}\left(x\right)}{w^{2}}+\frac{s_{3}\left(x\right)}{w}+\rho_{7}\left(x\right)\end{align*}

\end_inset

Because all of these are constructed from step functions, they are easily
 integrated over: the integrals are composed of triangle waves.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several properties of these functions should be noted.
 First, because the Walsh functions 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{m}$
\end_inset

 formed a complete orthonormal set for 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

, it follows that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{m}$
\end_inset

 also span 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 (because each 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{m}$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{m}$
\end_inset

 as a term).
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{m}$
\end_inset

 are also linearly independent (no 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{m}$
\end_inset

 can be written as a sum of the others, because each contains a term 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{m}$
\end_inset

 that cannot be cancelled out).
 They are not, however, orthogonal: in general, one has 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}\rho_{m}\left(x\right)\rho_{n}\left(x\right)dx\ne0$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $m=n2^{k}$
\end_inset

 for some (positive or negative) integer 
\begin_inset Formula $k.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By contrast, the 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{m}$
\end_inset

 are not linearly independent.
 Indeed, one readily verifies that 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2}=v_{1}/w$
\end_inset

, that 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{4}=v_{1}/w^{2}$
\end_inset

, and so on.
 Likewise, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{6}=v_{3}/w$
\end_inset

.
 In general, one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2^{k}m}=v_{m}/w^{k}$
\end_inset

 so that the 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{m}$
\end_inset

 are linearly independent of one-another if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is odd.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{c}$
\end_inset

 has a non-trivial kernel, it follows that the 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{m}$
\end_inset

 cannot span 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

