\begin_layout Section
The Isola Map 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Stefano Isola proposes studying a map of deceptive simplicity
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Iso03"

\end_inset

.
 Given by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
F(x)=\left\{ \begin{array}{c}
x/(1-x)\;\textrm{ if }\;0\leq x\leq1/2\\
(1-x)/x\;\textrm{ if }\;1/2\leq x\leq1\end{array}\right.\]

\end_inset

it is symmetric about 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1/2$
\end_inset

: that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)=F(1-x)$
\end_inset

, and has a very simple tent-like shape, and this is the source of the deception.
 One wants to hastily conclude that it is topologically equivalent to the
 standard tent map 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tau(x)=\left\{ \begin{array}{c}
2x\;\textrm{ if }\;0\leq x\leq1/2\\
2-2x\;\textrm{ if }\;1/2\leq x\leq1\end{array}\right.\]

\end_inset

and thus that the spectrum of its Frobenius-Perron Operator is identical
 to that of the Bernoulli Map, and that this map can be trivially brushed
 aside as belonging to that conjugacy class.
 Nothing could be farther from the truth.
 In fact, it is conjugate, but the conjugating function is the Minkowski
 Question Mark: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
F(x)=(?^{-1}\circ\tau\circ?)(x)\]

\end_inset

and so the relationship is anything but trivial.
 The easiest way to see this is to note that we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 are combinations of the modular group element 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
F(x)=\left\{ \begin{array}{c}
g_{C}^{-1}(x)\;\textrm{ if }\;0\leq x\leq1/2\\
(g_{C}^{-1}\circ r)(x)\;\textrm{ if }\;1/2\leq x\leq1\end{array}\right.\]

\end_inset

following the notation of earlier chapters, and
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tau(x)=\left\{ \begin{array}{c}
g_{D}^{-1}(x)\;\textrm{ if }\;0\leq x\leq1/2\\
(g_{D}^{-1}\circ r)(x)\;\textrm{ if }\;1/2\leq x\leq1\end{array}\right.\]

\end_inset

Just as we saw with the second sawtooth, the point dynamics of the Isola
 Map and the Tent Map are isomorphic to each other, but the eigenvalue spectra
 are inequivalent.
 The Ruelle-Frobenius-Perron operator for the Isola Map is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{P}f\right](x)=\frac{1}{\left(1+x\right)^{2}}\left[f\left(\frac{x}{x+1}\right)+f\left(\frac{1}{x+1}\right)\right]\]

\end_inset

Isola shows how the Gauss-Kuzmin-Wirsing operator can be constructed through
 some simple operator relationships on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 and so it is a worthwhile goal to attempt to solve 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

.
 As we will see below, this seems to be an even harder task.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Closely related is a modular variant of the Bernoulli shift, given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
A\left(y\right)=?^{-1}\left(\mbox{frac}\left(2?\left(y\right)\right)\right)=\begin{cases}
\frac{y}{1-y} & \mbox{ for }0\le y\le\frac{1}{2}\\
\frac{2y-1}{y} & \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{2}\le y\le1\end{cases}\label{eq:defn-A}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The associated transfer operator is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{A}f\right]\left(y\right)=\frac{1}{\left(1+y\right)^{2}}f\left(\frac{y}{1+y}\right)+\frac{1}{\left(2-y\right)^{2}}f\left(\frac{1}{2-y}\right)\]

\end_inset

which again has the curious relationship 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{A}?^{\prime}=?^{\prime}\]

\end_inset

as given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vep-mink2008"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The (Lack of a) Polynomial Basis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on our previous luck, we attempt to define the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 in the polynomial basis.
 First, we attempt an expansion at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 This leads to
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathcal{P}_{nk}\equiv & \left\langle n\left|\mathcal{P}\right|k\right\rangle \\
= & (-)^{n}\left[\left(\begin{array}{c}
k+n+1\\
k+1\end{array}\right)+\Theta_{k\leq n}(-)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n+1\\
k+1\end{array}\right)\right]\end{align*}

\end_inset

This matrix is not triangular, and is thus not directly solvable.
 It is also very ill-conditioned, making it not numerically tractable, at
 least, not in any simple fashion.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 gets large, the matrix elements grow exponentially on the diagonal.
 This is easily seen by applying Stirling's asymptotic formula for the factorial
 to the binomial; one easily gets 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\approx\frac{2^{n+1}}{\sqrt{2\pi n}}\exp\left(\frac{-(2k-n)^{2}}{2n}\right)\]

\end_inset

when 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 get large.
 Thus, along the diagonal, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{nn}\approx4^{n+1}/2\sqrt{\pi n}$
\end_inset

, and the matrix is not tractable numerically, and would be painful to work
 with analytically, without defining some sort of regulator.
 Thus, we are motivated to look at the expansion at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1/2$
\end_inset

.
 Here, however, the situation is not much better.
 Defining 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x-1/2$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{Q}f\right](x)=\frac{1}{\left(y+3/2\right)^{2}}\left[f\left(\frac{y+1/2}{y+3/2}\right)+f\left(\frac{1}{y+3/2}\right)\right]\]

\end_inset

we work through the same set of steps to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathcal{Q}_{nk}\equiv & \left\langle n\left|\mathcal{Q}\right|k\right\rangle \\
= & \left(\frac{-2}{3}\right)^{n+2}\left[\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
k+n+1\\
k+1\end{array}\right)+\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^{k}\;\sum_{p=0}^{\min(n,k)}\left(-3\right)^{p}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n+k-p+1\\
k+1\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
k\\
p\end{array}\right)\right]\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is far more complex, and only marginally less divergent: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}_{nn}\sim(16/9)^{n+1}$
\end_inset

.
 There is hardly any hope that a Taylor's expansion around any other value
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 will give a tractable result; the trick of using the Taylor's expansion
 to obtain polynomial eigenstates fails in this case.
 Indeed, it seems likely that the eigenstates will not be analytic, although
 it is not clear to me what theorem would establish or disprove this conjecture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The polynomial-basis matrix elements for this operator are much better behaved.
 They are given by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
M_{nk}\equiv\left\langle n\left|\mathcal{L}_{A}\right|k\right\rangle =\frac{1}{2^{2+n+k}}{n+k+1 \choose k+1}+\Theta_{n\ge k}\left(-1\right)^{k+n}{n+1 \choose k+1}\]

\end_inset

(Notice the direction of the Heaviside function is reversed, is this correct,
 or an error? XXX Needs double-checking).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The leading factor of two in the above makes all the difference in the world
 for this operator.
 This time, applying Stirling's formula to evaluate the matrix elements
 on the diagonal gives 
\begin_inset Formula \[
M_{nn}\approx1+\frac{0.76}{\sqrt{n}}\]

\end_inset

thus implying that this operator, at least, is not hopelessly badly behaved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The difference between the two is, perhaps, due to the former not being
 diagonalizable except in Jordan block form.
\end_layout

