\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 likewise expanded about 
\begin_inset Formula $x=b$
\end_inset

.
 With this expansion, the operator relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}f=g$
\end_inset

 becomes 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{g^{(m)}(b)}{m!}=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\mathcal{L}_{mn}^{(b,a)}\;\frac{f^{(n)}(a)}{n!}\]

\end_inset

which is taken to define the meaning of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{mn}^{(b,a)}$
\end_inset

.
 Without much difficulty, one discovers that the matrix elements are given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{mn}^{(b,a)}=(-1)^{m}\sum_{k=0}^{n}(-a)^{n-k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
k+m+1\\
m\end{array}\right)\,\zeta_{H}(k+m+2,1+b)\label{eq:general elts}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{H}(s,q)$
\end_inset

 is the Hurwitz zeta function:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\zeta_{H}(s,q)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{(n+q)^{s}}\]

\end_inset

Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $a=b=1/2$
\end_inset

, one obtains the expansion of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Briggs2003"

\end_inset

, which is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathcal{L}_{mn}^{(1/2,1/2)}= & (-1)^{m}\sum_{k=0}^{n}\left(\frac{-1}{2}\right)^{n-k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
k+m+1\\
m\end{array}\right)\,\times\\
 & \hspace{1em}\left[2^{m+k+2}\left(\zeta(k+m+2)-1\right)-\zeta(k+m+2)\right]\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All of these expressions for the matrix elements for the GKW operator have
 a common form.
 It consists of two summations: the outer summation, and the summation defining
 the Hurwitz zeta function.
 Exchanging the order of summation, one finds terms consisting of a series
 of polynomials, which are most simply expressed in terms of Gauss's hypergeomet
ric series: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Gamma_{mn}(x)\equiv(m+1)\,_{2}F_{1}\left[\begin{array}{c}
\begin{array}{cc}
-n\; & \; m+2\end{array}\\
2\end{array}\;;\; x\right]=\sum_{k=0}^{n}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
k+m+1\\
m\end{array}\right)(-x)^{k}\]

\end_inset

These have a curious superficial resemblance to the shifted Legendre polynomial
 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\widetilde{P}_{n}(x)\equiv\sum_{k=0}^{n}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
k+n\\
n\end{array}\right)(-x)^{k}\]

\end_inset

Switching the order of summation in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general elts"

\end_inset

 gives the following: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{mn}^{(b,a)}=(-1)^{m+n}a^{n}\sum_{j=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{(j+b)^{m+2}}\,_{2}F_{1}\left[\begin{array}{c}
\begin{array}{cc}
-n\; & \; m+2\end{array}\\
2\end{array}\;;\;\frac{-1}{a(j+b)}\right]\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Curiously, the above is in the form of the Mayer-Ruelle operator.
 This operator is a slightly generalized form of the GKW operator given
 by Dieter Mayer
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "May91"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{M}^{(s)}f\right](x)\equiv\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{(n+x)^{s}}f\left(\frac{1}{n+x}\right)\]

\end_inset

Then, taking 
\begin_inset Formula $s=m+2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x=b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=_{2}F_{1}\left[\begin{array}{c}
\begin{array}{cc}
-n\; & \; m+2\end{array}\\
2\end{array}\;;\;\frac{-x}{a}\right]$
\end_inset

, one has that the GKW matrix elements are just specific values resulting
 from the application of the Mayer-Ruelle operator to the hypergeometric
 series: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{mn}^{(b,a)}=(-1)^{m+n}a^{n}\left[\mathcal{M}^{(m+2)}f\right](b)\]

\end_inset

 The simplicity of this form can be further reinforces by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $a=b=1$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
G_{mn}=\left[\mathcal{M}^{(m+2)}f\right](1)\]

\end_inset

where, of course, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{mn}$
\end_inset

 are the matrix elements of the GKW operator as defined in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:GKW-matrix-elts"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following the same proceedures and definitions as above, the matrix elements
 of the Ruelle-Mayer operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}^{(s)}$
\end_inset

 may be written as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[\mathcal{M}^{(s)}\right]_{mn}^{(b,a)}=(-1)^{m}\sum_{k=0}^{n}(-a)^{n-k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
m+k+s-1\\
m\end{array}\right)\,\zeta_{H}(m+k+s,1+b)\label{eq:RM-general elts}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The above gets a bit easier to read if one sets 
\begin_inset Formula $a=b=1$
\end_inset

 to obtain
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{M}^{(s)}\right]_{mn}=(-1)^{m+n}\sum_{k=0}^{n}(-1)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
m+k+s-1\\
m\end{array}\right)\,\left[\zeta(m+k+s)-1\right]\]

\end_inset

which obviously reduces to the GKW operator for 
\begin_inset Formula $s=2$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
G_{mn}=(-1)^{m+n}\left[\mathcal{M}^{(2)}\right]_{mn}\]

\end_inset

The corresponding hypergeometric identity that comes into play is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{k=0}^{n}\left(-x\right)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
m+k+s-1\\
m\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
m+s-1\\
m\end{array}\right)\;_{2}F_{1}\left[\begin{array}{c}
\begin{array}{cc}
-n\; & \; m+s\end{array}\\
s\end{array}\;;\; x\right]\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a final note, recall that the Hurwitz zeta may be expressed as the polygamma
 function for integer arguments, where the polygamma functions are the chain
 of logarithmic derivatives of the gamma function.
 Thus, one may also expresses the matrix elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 in the curious form 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{mn}^{(b,a)}=\frac{(-a)^{n+1}}{m!}\sum_{k=0}^{n}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\left(\frac{1}{a}\right)^{k+1}\frac{1}{(k+1)!}\,\frac{d^{k+1}}{dx^{k+1}}\psi^{(m)}(1+b)\]

\end_inset

Here, the curious operator making an appearance is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[P_{n,y}f\right](x)=\sum_{k=0}^{n}\left(-y\right)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\,\frac{f^{(k)}(x)}{k!}\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{(k)}(x)$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{n,y}$
\end_inset

is upper-triangular, with all eigenvalues equal to 1, and all eigenvectors
 being polynomials (or analytic series for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 not an integer).
 
\end_layout

