\begin_layout Standard
This appendix demonstrates the behaviour of the transfer operator under
 the action of a similarity transformation.
 The demonstration proceeds using the simplest, most basic manipulations
 possible, so as to be easy to verify.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a differentiable function 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha:X\to X$
\end_inset

, the transfer operator (Perron-Frobenius-Ruelle operator) 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\alpha}:\mathcal{F}\left(X\right)\to\mathcal{F}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 is a bounded linear operator acting on a space of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 One possible, simple definition for this operator is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{\alpha}f\right]\left(x\right)=\sum_{y\in\alpha^{-1}\left(x\right)}\frac{1}{\left|\alpha^{\prime}\left(y\right)\right|}f\left(y\right)\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{F}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 denotes the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 The derivation of the similarity transform proceeds by substituting the
 similarity relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\phi^{-1}\circ\beta\circ\phi$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:X\to V$
\end_inset

 being one-to-one and onto (and so being uniquely invertible), and being
 differentiable, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 can be defined.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta:V\to V$
\end_inset

 is a function conjugate to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,$
\end_inset

 and is differentiable as well.
 Substituting, one then has:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left[\mathcal{L}_{\alpha}f\right]\left(x\right)= & \sum_{y\in\left(\phi^{-1}\circ\beta\circ\phi\right)^{-1}\left(x\right)}\frac{1}{\left|\left(\phi^{-1}\circ\beta\circ\phi\right)^{\prime}\left(y\right)\right|}f\left(y\right)\\
= & \sum_{\phi\left(y\right)\in\left(\beta\circ\phi\right)^{-1}\left(x\right)}\frac{1}{\left|\left(\phi^{-1}\circ\beta\circ\phi\right)^{\prime}\left(y\right)\right|}f\left(y\right)\end{align*}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $w=\phi(y)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v=\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left[\mathcal{L}_{\alpha}f\right]\left(\phi^{-1}\left(v\right)\right)= & \sum_{w\in\beta^{-1}\left(v\right)}\frac{1}{\left|\left(\phi^{-1}\circ\beta\circ\phi\right)^{\prime}\left(\phi^{-1}\left(w\right)\right)\right|}f\left(\phi^{-1}\left(w\right)\right)\\
= & \sum_{w\in\beta^{-1}\left(v\right)}\frac{f\left(\phi^{-1}\left(w\right)\right)}{\left|\left(\phi^{-1\prime}\circ\beta\right)\left(w\right)\cdot\beta^{\prime}\left(w\right)\cdot\left(\phi^{\prime}\circ\phi^{-1}\right)\left(w\right)\right|}\end{align*}

\end_inset

Observe that, for all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in\beta^{-1}\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

, one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\phi^{-1\prime}\circ\beta\right)\left(w\right)=\phi^{-1\prime}\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

 and so this term can be brought out of the summation.
 Next, one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $1=\left(\phi\circ\phi^{-1}\right)^{\prime}=\left(\phi^{\prime}\circ\phi^{-1}\right)\cdot\phi^{-1\prime}$
\end_inset

 and so one has 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{1}{\left|\left(\phi^{\prime}\circ\phi^{-1}\right)\left(v\right)\right|}\left[\mathcal{L}_{\alpha}f\right]\left(\phi^{-1}\left(v\right)\right)=\sum_{w\in\beta^{-1}\left(v\right)}\frac{1}{\left|\beta^{\prime}\left(w\right)\right|}\left(\frac{\left(f\circ\phi^{-1}\right)\left(w\right)}{\left|\left(\phi^{\prime}\circ\phi^{-1}\right)\left(w\right)\right|}\right)\]

\end_inset

Define an operator 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\phi}:\mathcal{F}\left(X\right)\to\mathcal{F}\left(V\right)$
\end_inset

 that acts on 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{F}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[S_{\phi}f\right]\left(v\right)=\frac{\left(f\circ\phi^{-1}\right)\left(v\right)}{\left|\left(\phi^{\prime}\circ\phi^{-1}\right)\left(v\right)\right|}\]

\end_inset

Then the previous equation can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[S_{\phi}\mathcal{L}_{\alpha}f\right]\left(v\right)=\left[\mathcal{L}_{\beta}S_{\phi}f\right]\left(v\right)\]

\end_inset

Since this holds for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

, one must have 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\beta}=S_{\phi}\mathcal{L}_{\alpha}S_{\phi}^{-1}\]

\end_inset

where clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\phi}^{-1}=S_{\phi^{-1}}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the two transfer operators are conjugate to one-another when the
 functions generating them are similar.
 The primary ingredient for the above derivation was that the similarity
 transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 needed to be differentiable, in order to make the manipulations legitimate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In fact, the conjugacy transformation leaves the spectrum of the operators
 unchanged.
 To see this, one must switch to slightly more abstract language: first,
 one must establish that the transfer operator is bounded (as, indeed, it
 is) and that it is expressible as a nuclear operator, so that it can be
 written as a countable sum of (bounded, summable) eigenvalues and basis
 vectors.
 
\end_layout

